observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Review thoroughly the Check Registers from Treasury Office and identify all the unreleased checks at the end of the year. Effect the necessary adjustment by restoring the Cash in Bank previously credited and set up Accounts Payable for the unreleased checks.  At the beginning of the ensuing year, reverse the adjustment made;
Determine the original entry of the book error and make the necessary adjusting entries to correct the error made;
Identify the nature of the credit memo/deposits made and recognize them in the books using the proposed journal entry;
Cash In Bank					P20,404.02
Prior Year Adjustments or liability Account			P20,404.02
Present the adjusted balance of Cash in Bank Account in the financial statement pursuant to the provisions of International Public Sector Accounting Standards and COA Circular 96-011.

We recommended that Management:
make a proper written requests to the Source Agencies (SA) for authority to utilize the unused funds for projects or endeavors that are congruent to the PPAs of the SAs or to transfer the same to the General Fund so that these will be appropriated to accomplish the PPAs of the Municipality.  If such requests are disapproved, instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to facilitate the immediate return of the unutilized balances to the SAs or to the Bureau of Treasury, so that these will be used by the national government for social services or other PPAs of the government;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to facilitate the reversion of the unutilized balances of the Trust Liabilities and Other Payables to the general funds, particularly those projects which are already completed, or the purpose of which were no longer feasible, or the implementation were already abandoned, so that these will be re-appropriated for other endeavors of the Municipality;
Require the Municipal Accountant to review the entries made in the Other Payables account and to draw the proper adjusting entries to reclassify them correctly, pursuant to COA Circular 2015-009; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to adhere to the proper recording of fund transfers in accordance with the description of the accounts presented in the aforementioned COA Circular, to properly present the accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Management:
Expedite the completion of the partially completed 2023 and prior years’ development projects;
Realign or reprogram the current year savings of 2023 and those of prior years for development PPAs, so that these will not remain idle, and their money value will translate into the betterment of the lives of the people of Aritao;
Evaluate the unimplemented projects if these are still necessary, appropriate, or incidental to efficient and effective local governance, and are essential to the promotion of the general welfare of the people, as well as if these are procurement-and-implementation-ready.  Otherwise, realign or reprogram the funds to other priority development PPAs that can be implemented immediately; and
Ensure that the implementation of these projects under the 20% development funds are in line with the provisions of DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1, s. 2020.

We recommended that the Management should:
Instruct all the concerned personnel to ensure that all dates and other necessary information required in the various documentary requirements attached to the procurement of various goods must be filled out properly, completely and truthfully to ascertain compliance to applicable procedures, rules and regulations;
Instruct the GSO to include the name of the canvassers in the RFQ to clearly establish their accountability as to the veracity of the canvass of prices or request for quotations made;
Inform the Suppliers and all the government employees of the Municipality that goods must be delivered directly to the GSO Office, to be duly accepted by them and inspected by the authorized inspector, before these are released to the end-users who will accept the goods through the RIS form; Ensure that the procedure of acquisition, requisition and issuance of goods are followed religiously;
Require the accounting office and treasury office to ensure that documentary requirements are all present and completely filled out before payments for these are processed and released, in compliance with Section 4 of PD No. 1445; and
Take measures to promote transparency and accountability in the management of public finances pursuant to Article 9, Chapter II of the United Nations Convention against Corruption (UNCAC).

We recommended that the Management require:
The Contractors of the previous and newly constructed projects to submit the as-built plans for recording, safekeeping and future references;
All concerned personnel to comply with the documentary requirements prescribed by COA Circular 2023-004, particularly for the disbursement of progress and final payments of various projects of the Municipality to ensure the transaparency and compliance with rules and regulations of the transactions;
The Municipal Accountant  and Municipal Treasurer to vigilantly ensure that the documentary requirements of the DVs are complete and proper before these are processed, approved, and paid to claimants; and
The responsible offices and personnel for the aforementioned documentary deficiencies to submit to COA Office, if available and possible,  or to explain in writing why these should not be suspended or disallowed in audit.

We recommended that Management:
Properly fill out the supporting documents so that these will serve their very purpose and for transparency purposes;
Designate technically knowledgeable and capable personnel who must conduct pre- and post- inspection repairs to be more effective in addressing the needs of repair and maintenance, not just for motor vehicles, but all the PPEs of the agency;
Require the preparation and maintenance of a repair history record of each vehicle, and obtain warranty certificates from suppliers or repair and maintenance service providers, in compliance with the requirements set forth under COA Circular No. 2023-004;
Attach also before- and after-pictures, if applicable, to document the repairs made; and
Instruct the Accounting and Treasury office to ensure that documentary requirements for repairs and maintenance are strictly adhered to before processing and releasing any disbursements relative thereof.

We recommended that the Management:
Investigate the discrepancies of the quotations and assertions of the Suppliers and to require the responsible persons to justify the irregularity of the quotations and the preference to obtain goods in other Municipality despite the availability of Suppliers within the vicinity of the Municipality, and submit justification why the excess should not be disallowed in audit;
Require the GSO and BAC to review the process of procurement based on rules and regulations, streamline these processes, and require each office and concerned personnel to abide strictly and religiously;
Require the Accounting and Treasury Office to be vigilant in the pre-audit of documentary requirements to ensure that the attached documents are authentic, complete in details and proper before funds are disbursed; and
Require each office and concerned personnel to ensure that procurements are conducted with transparency and integrity, and that the most competitive prices are obtained in line with the mandate of the government to use funds prudently and judiciously.

We recommended that the Management:
Instruct the BAC and other concerned personnel to review the procurement process of the Municipality and make necessary changes or improvement to hasten or shorten the procurement process without violating the provisions of Section 37 and 38 of Article XI of RA 9184.  The BAC and other officials must be mindful of the allowable time granted for every kind of procurement;
Communicate with the Supplier to impose and collect the liquidated damages amounting to P140,000.00 for the delay incurred on the delivery of the Mobile Clinic, to avoid issuance of Notice of Disallowance;
Strictly adhere to the provisions of RA 9184 and its revised IRR, particularly the observation of timelines for each activity of the procurement process, so that it will not exceed the allowable period of procurement; and
Practice the imposition of liquidated damages to the defaulting Suppliers.

We recommended that the Management:
Stop the practice of deleting and reducing scope of works to accommodate positive variation orders and ensure that the changes are within the general scope of the project as bid and awarded.  Otherwise, similar occurrences will be disallowed in audit;
Concerned personnel must be more circumspect in approving variation orders and ensure the strict adherence of the provisions of RA 9184 with regard to the preparation and submission of variation orders, as prescribed by Item 1.5 of Annex E of RIRR of RA 9184;
Require the Project Engineer to submit the SWA, as of the end of the contract term, in order to compute the liquidated damages; and
Require the Project Engineer and other concerned personnel to submit written justification why the variation order was still accommodated despite the fact that it is already beyond the contract term.

This has been discussed in the previous Annual Audit Report but the same practice remained, thus we reiterated our recommendation that the Management:
Stop the payment of TAs to the officials who are already assigned with or used government vehicle;
Require the refund of the transportation allowance totaling P183,286.16 granted to concerned employees.  Otherwise, these will be disallowed in audit;
Instruct the accounting office to ensure that the grant of TAs is aligned with the provisions of various law, rules, and regulations.

We recommended that the Management:
Review the reconciling items in the bank reconciliation statements and examine items which have been outstanding for more than one (1) month and prepare journal entries to adjust/correct the book balance;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to henceforth, prepare and submit Report of Checks Issued every end of the month to the Accounting Office based on the released checks to claimants;
Advise the claimants of unreleased checks to duly acknowledge the Check Register from the Treasury Office by completely filling out the “Received by” portion including the date when the check was received; and
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and submit a Schedule of Unreleased Checks at year-end to the Accounting Office for the preparation of JEV to restore the cash equivalent of unreleased checks.

We recommended that the Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to compute and impose the liquidated damages to defaulting suppliers/contractors to encourage prompt deliveries of goods to the Municipality and to ensure that all documentary requirements are all in order before processing the disbursement vouchers;
Require the Procuring Office personnel to ensure that all details of the Purchase Orders are provided for proper accountability and transparency;
Require the Supply Officer or authorized personnel to accomplish the Inspection and Acceptance Reports (IARs) completely and properly;
Require the Supply Officer or authorized personnel to ensure that only actual goods delivered are included on the delivery receipts, and subsequent deliveries must be covered with different delivery receipts to reflect the actual flow of goods.  Also, ensure that these DRs are duly dated and the receipt of goods by the proper authority is clearly indicated on the space provided for;
Direct all suppliers to make deliveries to the Property/Supply Office who shall be accountable and liable for the receipt and inspection of the goods delivered; and
Develop and institute measures to address the lapses on the procurement procedure.

We recommended Management to:
(1) formulate a system of procurement on the issuance of goods so that all procured goods will be recorded as assets first; 
(2) upon issuance / release of goods, prepare the necessary RIS and the ICS; 
(3) maintain a copy of the ICS for safekeeping and issue the other copy to the recipient for proper accountability; and 
(4) prepare a monthly Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI) and forward to the Accounting Office for the preparation of journal entry to record the expenses incurred for the month. Attached as Annex B is the list of tangible assets considered as inventories, the ICS form to be used and the instructions of filling up the ICS form. 
(5) adherence with the rules and regulations under the GAM as mentioned above is encouraged.

We recommended Management to: 
cause the immediate liquidation of the unliquidated cash advances of ₱95,760.00;
refrain from maintaining unliquidated cash advances at the end of the year; 
monitor all cash advances and advice all the accountable officers of the responsibility with respect to their cash advances and its liquidation; 
be reminded further that unused cash advance shall be refunded at the end of the year and new cash advance is withdrawn at the beginning of the year;
and strict adherence with the provisions of stated above should be complied with.

